results.name: Number of partitions of n into six primes.
link: Alois P. Heinz, Table of n, a(n) for n = 12..10000
Index entries for sequences related to partitions
formula: a(n) = Sum_{m=1..floor(n/6)} Sum_{l=m..floor((n-m)/5)} Sum_{k=l..floor((n-l-m)/4)} Sum_{j=k..floor((n-k-l-m)/3)} Sum_(i=j..floor((n-j-k-l-m)/2)} A010051(i) * A010051(j) * A010051(k) * A010051(l) * A010051(m) * A010051(n-i-j-k-l-m). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Apr 17 2019
a(n) = [x^n y^6] Product_{k>=1} 1/(1 - y*x^prime(k)). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Apr 18 2019
example: a(17) = 3 because there are 3 partitions of 17 into six primes: [2,2,2,2,2,7], [2,2,2,3,3,5] and [2,3,3,3,3,3].
